You should learn from this discrepancy that there is no univer=
sally correct dharma. As Krishna says in Bhagad Gita, one must follow one's=
 own dharma and not someone else's dharma. Each person has a unique "own dh=
arma" that is decided by Nature based on what one did in the past, what deb=
ts one has from the past and what desires one harbored in the past. For one=
 person, serving guru may be the correct dharma. For one person, killing on=
e's gurus may be the correct dharma (e.g. Arjuna).
=A0
The universal thumbr=
ules of dharma shastras are for generic guidance until one knows one's own =
dharma with some level of confidence. They are neither perfect nor unbreaka=
ble.
=A0
One's conscience keeps telling one what one's dharma is. It keeps =
making a noise from within heart whenever one veers off from one's own dhar=
ma. However, our vision is clouded by our desires, likes, dislikes, conditi=
oning and agendas and we fail to see our dharma.
=A0
As we follow our dharm=
a more and more and as we become more and more detached to the good and bad=
 (!) consequences of following our dharma, the voice of our conscience beco=
mes louder and clearer and we can know our dharma with more and more confid=
ence. Doing dharma better makes it easier to be detached. Being detached ma=
kes it easier to know one's dharma better. Doing one's dharma (karma) and d=
etachment (jnana) feed and enhance each other. One needs to somehow or the =
other increase them beyond some threshold and fall into the groove.
=A0
