>Namaste friends, =A0 Ther=
e was a discussion on Lord Vishnu's Dasavataras on a limited access forum o=
n Facebook. A learned friend wrote that "Krshna is the God-man", "Previous =
Avatars are a build-up to this stage" and "Buddha after Krshna is like goin=
g back from the linear progression of spirituality that the Avatars manifes=
t one after the other upto Krshna". =A0 I want to emphatically disagree wit=
h this notion that Dasavatars of a "linear progression of spirituality..upt=
o Krshna". =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 Each ava=
tara represents an aspect of Supreme in a perfected form. =A0 Maharshi Para=
sara equated dasavataras with planets. For example, Rama, Krishna and Naras=
imha are Sun, Moon and Mars, respectively. =A0 We also know that Sun, Moon,=
 Mars, Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn, Rahu and Ketu are personifications =
of soul, mind, energy/initiative/drive, learning spirit, wisdom/discriminat=
ion, spirit of enjoyment/being happy, patience/discipline,
 spirit of innov=
ation/breaking barriers and detachment (respectively). =A0 Correspondingly,=
 each avatara is an expression of that aspect of Supreme in a perfected for=
m. Each story is an example of how that aspect operates. =A0 Lord Rama's st=
ory is a perfected example of how soul operates. Lord Krishna's story is a =
perfected example of how mind operates. Lord Vamana's story is a perfected =
example of how wisdom/discrimination operates. Lord Narasimha's story is a =
perfected example of how energy/drive/initiative operates. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=
=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 Now, let us remember one basic th=
ing. Soul in us, mind in us, energy in us, learning spirit in us, wisdom in=
 us, happiness in us, discipline/patience in us - all these are different m=
anifestations of the same Self. However, when Self manifests as these diffe=
rent aspects, it has different qualities and plays different roles. There i=
s no comparison between them. =A0 We MAY focus on one aspect of us first,
 =
perfect it and then perfect other aspects through it. But, we need balance =
between all aspects in the end. Similarly, these different aspects of Supre=
me Being are incomparable and are in a balance working together in the Cosm=
os. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 One who is fasc=
inated by the qualities of soul may like the story that demonstrates how so=
ul operates; one who is fascinated by the qualities of mind may like the st=
ory that demonstrates how mind operates, and one who is fascinated by the q=
ualities of wisdom may like the story that demonstrates how wisdom operates=
. And so on. But this is just a matter of taste and subjective preference. =
=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 Let us focus on Ram=
a and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind. Soul is seen as a representative of god =
in us, because of some basic attributes of it. It is the higher self and ha=
s no agendas, no likes or dislikes. =A0 Once mind fancies a separate existe=
nce with some
 agendas/desires, soul supports the individualized consciousn=
ess stemming from that fancy and sees it as its dharma. It lends strength a=
nd support to EVERY aspect of this individualized consciousness (e.g. mind,=
 energy, intellect, learning ability, enjoyment, discipline etc). It suppor=
ts them fully and yet has no desires/agendas/likes/dislikes of its own! It =
impassionately witnesses and records all of one's agendas and karmas so tha=
t Laws of Nature give proper fruits later on. It does all that despite full=
 awareness that it is neither doing those karmas nor receiving the fruits. =
As mind and other aspects of the individualized consciousness entertain the=
 notion that they are doing things and begetting the fruits, soul supports =
them fully in this play. It sees that as its dharma and does it impassionat=
ely. =A0 Now, does this sound exciting? Perhaps not to all. This functional=
ity of an impassionate witness supporting the play, may not seem interestin=
g enough
 to some. =A0 On the other hand, mind has likes, dislikes and agen=
das. It is constantly pursuing those agendas, getting things and achieving =
things. Movement of mind is what keeps the individualization going!!! Thoug=
h soul is the support for everything else in the individualized consciousne=
ss, soul is a witness doing its dharma impassionately. It is mind that keep=
s the individualization going and brings in agendas and passion and even de=
cides/affects every entity's dharma. That way, mind is really the "boss" of=
 the individualization. No wonder Krishna's life appeals more to one who ma=
y be excited by this description! =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=
=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 Lord Krishna is obviously awe-inspiring, but let me put Ram=
a's life in perspective. =A0 Rama's life demonstrates how soul operates. At=
 a young age, he received Brahma Jnana from Vasishtha and became realized. =
Yet, he did whatever was his "dharma". He helped Vishwamitra. Soon after ma=
rriage, he was given
 kingdom. At the last moment, his father banished him =
to forest at the behest of his step-mother and his step-brother was given t=
he throne. He had no complaints. Though his father, step-mother and step-br=
other felt guilty to various degrees, he himself supported and consoled all=
 three and followed his dharma impassionately. Though he knew leaving Sita =
in the forest with Lakshmana and going after the golden deer would cause pr=
oblems, he did it impassionately when Sita insisted. When she was kidnapped=
 by Ravana, he searched for her and fought the battle. He never faulted Sit=
a for forcing him to leave her or faulted Lakshmana for leaving her later. =
He accepted every life situation with no complaints and did the best possib=
le action then. Even as he killed Ravana, he did so without hatred or anger=
, but as his impassionate dharma. Even as Ravana was dying, he went to him =
and respectfully learned some subjects that were going to disappear with Ra=
vana! =A0 Rama
 is a perfect example of a liberated man with no desires or =
agendas who impassionately discharges one's dharma arising from the momentu=
m of karmas before liberation. THAT is basically what soul does! =A0 *=A0=
=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 As another example, let us =
look at Lord Vaamana. His story is a perfect demonstration of how wisdom/di=
scrimination operates. =A0 He was born as a learned pygmy. He filled the en=
tire cosmos to rid earth of a charitable demon king with many great qualiti=
es. =A0 Wisdom/discrimination makes one humble and unassuming. When one is =
doing good work but tainted with demonic qualities (e.g. pride or attachmen=
t), one's discrimination is not pleased until that pride is suppressed. Whe=
n wisdom fills one's entire consciousness, then demonic qualities are compl=
etely suppressed. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 P=
lease think about the other avataras. The stories can be understood as perf=
ect demonstrations of how various aspects of
 our consciousness operate, ba=
sed on clues from Maharshi Parasara. =A0 Let us not compare Dasavataras, bu=
t celebrate each of them separately. Of course, if you are more attracted t=
o one of them, please think about that avatara more and develop devotion. T=
hey are ALL capable of relieving us from samsara. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=
=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 By the way, happy Hanumajjayanti to those =
who celebrate it today (there are different schools of thought). =A0 Best r=
egards, Narasimha -------- Astrology & Spirituality Resources: http://www.V=
